description:
File: rust/lichen-rpl/src/trickle.rs
Lines: 175-185

The try_reset() method can be called from Stopped state, but begin_interval() expects to transition TO WaitingTransmit:
```rust
pub fn try_reset(&mut self, now: u32, rand_offset: u32) -> Result<(), InvalidTrickleTransition> {
    if self.interval != self.imin {
        self.interval = self.imin;
        self.begin_interval(now, rand_offset)?;  // May fail
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

Looking at the state machine:
- Stopped -> WaitingTransmit is allowed (line 30)

So this actually works. However, the issue is that reset() (non-try version at line 171-172) silently ignores the error:
```rust
pub fn reset(&mut self, now: u32, rand_offset: u32) {
    let _ = self.try_reset(now, rand_offset);
}
```

If try_reset is called when the timer is in an unexpected state (e.g., due to a bug or race condition in the caller), the error would be silently swallowed.

Severity: P3 - The state machine actually allows the transition, but the silent error suppression pattern is risky.

Fix: Consider logging or asserting in non-try versions, or removing them entirely and requiring callers to handle errors.
